# Flutter UI — responsive & overflow rules

When adding or editing UI under `mobile/lib/`:

## Layout & overflow

- Prefer `Expanded`, `Flexible`, `Wrap`, `FittedBox`, and scroll views (`ListView`, `CustomScrollView`, `SingleChildScrollView`) so content never overflows at any width.
- Avoid `Row`/`Column` children with unbounded intrinsic width/height without flex or scroll.
- For `ListTile` actions on variable widths, use `PopupMenuButton`, `OverflowBar`, or a custom row with `Expanded` + ellipsis instead of a tight `trailing` `Row` of multiple controls.

## Sizing

- Avoid raw pixel `width`/`height` except where the platform requires it (e.g. touch targets, 1px dividers, fixed thumbnail size in a list). Prefer fractions of `MediaQuery.sizeOf(context)`, `LayoutBuilder` / `SliverLayoutBuilder`, and `AspectRatio`.
- Use `ConstrainedBox` / `BoxConstraints(maxWidth: …)` for dialogs and forms; use `dialogContentMaxWidth` from `core/responsive/responsive_layout.dart` instead of hardcoded dialog widths.

## Design tokens

- Use `AppSpacing` (`core/responsive/app_spacing.dart`) for padding and gaps instead of magic numbers.
- Use `AppBreakpoints` / `context.breakpointTier` (`core/responsive/responsive_context.dart`) for adaptive layout (mobile &lt; 600, tablet 600–1024, desktop ≥ 1024).
- For product grids, use `ResponsiveProductSliverGrid` (`widgets/responsive_sliver_grid.dart`) or `productGridCrossAxisCount` / `productGridAspectRatio` from `responsive_layout.dart`.

## Navigation rail (Material 3.41+)

- If `NavigationRail.extended` is `true`, set `labelType` to `null` or `NavigationRailLabelType.none` only.

## New screens

- Long or unknown-height content: wrap in a scroll view or use `AppScrollablePage` where a centered, max-width layout is appropriate (`core/responsive/responsive_layout.dart`).
